{
  "text": "An excited fluorescent molecule cannot be re-excited until it relaxes to the ground state. The occupation time of the excitons on a fluorescent molecule, i.e., the excited state lifetime or the time between two consecutive generations of excitons, is an exponential random variable [CITATION_1] . Additionally, we know that exciton generations are independent events [CITATION_2] . Therefore, the exciton generation is described by a Poisson process.",
  "correct_citation": {
